'''{{ill|Yunomine Ōji|ja|湯の峰王子|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yunomine Ōji|1=Yunomine Ōji Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11563413}}''' is one of the {{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} shrines, located in {{ill|Yunomine Onsen|en|Yunomine Onsen|WD=Q11563414|lt=Yunomine Onsen|1=Yunomine Onsen}}, {{ill|Tanabe, Wakayama|en|Tanabe, Wakayama|WD=Q304266|lt=Tanabe, Wakayama|1=Tanabe, Wakayama}}, Japan. It is situated on a hill behind {{ill|Tōkō-ji (Tanabe)|ja|東光寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōkō-ji (Tanabe)|1=Tōkō-ji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11526024}}, within the historic {{ill|Kumano Kodō|en|Kumano Kodō|WD=Q17050475|lt=Kumano Kodō|1=Kumano Kodō}}, a designated [[National Historic Site of Japan]] since 2000.

== Overview ==
Despite being part of the {{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}}, Yunomine Ōji is rarely mentioned in medieval pilgrimage records, such as those by {{ill|Fujiwara no Teika|en|Fujiwara no Teika|WD=Q378425|lt=Fujiwara no Teika|1=Fujiwara no Teika}}. During the height of the Kumano pilgrimage, routes primarily followed the {{ill|Kumano River|en|Kumano River|WD=Q1972071|lt=Kumano River|1=Kumano River}} downstream from {{ill|Kumano Hongū Taisha|en|Kumano Hongū Taisha|WD=Q705035|lt=Kumano Hongū Taisha|1=Kumano Hongū Taisha}} to {{ill|Shingu|en|Shingu|WD=Q475200|lt=Shingū, Wakayama|1=Shingu}}, bypassing Yunomine.

The earliest historical reference appears in a 1326 document from {{ill|Ninna-ji|en|Ninna-ji|WD=Q1202871|lt=Ninna-ji|1=Ninna-ji}}, with more mentions in the 15th century. The shrine likely became significant later due to the practice of ritual purification in hot springs (湯垢離, *yu-gori*) before worship at Kumano Hongū Taisha.

The current shrine was rebuilt after a fire in 1903 destroyed the original structure along with Tōkō-ji's main hall.

== Transportation ==
* From {{ill|Shingū Station|en|Shingū Station|WD=Q5357415|lt=Shingū Station|1=Shingū Station}} (JR {{ill|Kisei Main Line|en|Kisei Main Line|WD=Q582803|lt=Kisei Main Line|1=Kisei Main Line}}): approx. 60 minutes by {{ill|Kumano Kōtsu|ja|熊野交通|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōtsu|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 熊野御坊南海バス|1=Kumano Gobo Nankai Bus|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11568871}} bus
* From {{ill|Kii-Tanabe Station|en|Kii-Tanabe Station|WD=Q2888653|lt=Kii-Tanabe Station|1=Kii-Tanabe Station}}: approx. 90 minutes by {{ill|Ryujin Bus|ja|龍神バス|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryujin Bus|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 龍神自動車|1=Ryūjin Bus|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11679334}}
* From {{ill|Yamato-Yagi Station|en|Yamato-Yagi Station|WD=Q8047973|lt=Yamato-Yagi Station|1=Yamato-Yagi Station}} (Kintetsu): direct bus via {{ill|Totsukawa|en|Totsukawa|WD=Q1202740|lt=Totsukawa, Nara|1=Totsukawa}} (approx. 5 hr 20 min)
* All buses stop at "Yunomine Onsen" bus stop.

